# Bandit Level 4

## Goal
Find the only human-readable file among many files inside the `inhere` directory.

## What I learned
- How to use the `file` command to check what type a file is
- The difference between human-readable and binary files
- How to read files that start with a dash using `./`

## My Approach

```bash
# Moved into the inhere directory
cd inhere

# Checked each file one by one using the file command
file ./-file00
file ./-file01
file ./-file02
file ./-file03
file ./-file04
file ./-file05
file ./-file06
file ./-file07
file ./-file08

# Most returned "data" meaning binary — not readable
# -file07 returned "ASCII text" — that's the one!

# Read the file
cat ./-file07
```

## Why it works
The `file` command reads a file and tells you what type it is.
Binary files contain machine data that looks like gibberish to humans.
ASCII text files contain readable characters — that's where the password lives.

```
./-file00: data          ← binary, skip
./-file01: data          ← binary, skip
./-file07: ASCII text    ← human readable, this is it!
```

## Key commands learned
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `file ./filename` | Check what type a file is |
| ASCII text | Human readable file |
| data | Binary file — not readable |

## What I'd do differently next time
Use `file ./*` to check all files at once instead of one by one —
much faster when there are lots of files!

